                        <div>
                            <div id="be-doc-text"><p/><strong>cholera (<strong>kol</strong>-er-&#x103;) n.</strong>  an acute infection of the small intestine by the bacterium Vibrio cholerae, which causes severe vomiting and diarrhoea (known as <em>ricewater stools</em>) leading to dehydration. The disease is contracted from contaminated food or drinking water and often occurs in epidemics. Initial treatment is concentrated on replacing the fluid loss by oral rehydration therapy; tetracycline eradicates the bacteria and hastens recovery. The mortality rate in untreated cases is over 50%. Vaccination against cholera is effective for only 6&#x2013;9 months.<br/></div>
